        <body>
            <head><name type="stone">CIIC 97. <placeName type="townland">Ballyhank</placeName> 
                    I</name>, Co. <placeName type="county">Cork</placeName></head>
            <ab><rs>National Monuments Service Record Number: <ref
                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=CO085-067003-"
                >CO085-067003-</ref>
                </rs></ab>
            <div type="description" n="site type">
                <head>Site Type</head>
                <p>Souterrain</p>
            </div>
            <div type="description">
                <head>Description</head>
                <div type="description" n="site">
                    <head>Site</head>
                    <p>A souterrain (CO085-067002-) in the SW quadrant of a ringfort (CO085-067001-). 
                        <q>The souterrain was a passage 52' long, in three sections, 18', 16' and 18'
                            long respectively, on a slight zig-zag plan and with no expansion at
                            either end</q>
                        <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"><bibl>(<author>Macalister</author>
                                <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >92-3</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="monument">
                    <head>Monument</head>
                    <p>1 of 6 Ogam stones re-used in the construction of a souterrain. The top of a broken stone.
                        <rs type="material"></rs>
                        <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"><bibl>(<author>Macalister</author>
                                <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >93</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. <rs type="dimensions">
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="height">0.60</measure>m x
                                <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="width">0.30</measure>m x
                                <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="depth">0.10</measure>m
                                <ref type="bibliog" target="#POW1997">(<bibl><author>Power</author> 
                                    et al <date when="1997">1997</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >165</biblScope></bibl>)</ref></rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="text">
                    <head>Text</head>
                    <p><q>Inscription in minute scores, like rather straggling <rs type="execution">knife-cuts</rs>, on two angles, up-top-down...
                        This inscription is a palimpsest</q> <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"
                                    >(<bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >93</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. On the opposite angle <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"
                                        ><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                                            (<date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                                >93-4</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> described what he considered to be a copy of the original inscription on the stone (DIOBI), overwritten by the --LL MAQI VORRTIGURN. 
                        This 'copy' <q>...has been scratched in minute pin-scrapes on the unoccupied part of the second inscribed angle, perhaps by the representatives of the earlier owner. 
                        Of the original text, the initial DI is broken off, but can be restored from the later copy; the O remains, its notches flanking the proximal ends of the 1L; B is a thin scratch 
                        between the L's: 2I<hi rend="superscript">1</hi> is at the proximal end of 2L; 2I<hi rend="superscript">2</hi> is between the scores of 2L; 2I<hi rend="superscript">3</hi> was in a (now broken) 
                            place before the M; 2I<hi rend="superscript">4</hi> is extinguished by the M; and 2I<hi rend="superscript">5</hi> is between the 
                        M and the A, inducing Brash's misreading MOQI. The restoration of the name is legible on the second angle, but of the second I, the first notch alone remains clear: the remaining 
                        notches of this letter are rubbed, and are traceable only with difficulty</q>. While this earlier inscription suggested by Macalister is possible, it is far from certain.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="ga">
                <head xml:lang="en">Transliteration</head>
                <ab>
                    <lb/><w><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown"></gap>LL</w>
                    <w lemma="MAQI" type="formula">MAQI</w>
                    <persName><w lemma="VORRTIGURN">VORR/TIGU<unclear reason="damage">R</unclear>/N</w></persName>
                    </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <head>Translation</head>
                <p><q>... son of Foirtchern</q></p>
            </div>
            <div type="figure">
                <head>Images</head>
                <div type="figure" n="three-dimensional-model">
                    <head>3D model</head>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="photographs">
                    <head>Photographs</head>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="drawings">
