                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>The name VORRTIGURN is a compound of OIr <hi rend="italic">for</hi> 'on, over' and Welsh <hi rend="italic">Gwrtheyrn</hi> (OIr <hi rend="italic">tigern</hi>)  'lord'  
                        <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1991">(<bibl><author>McManus</author> <date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >105</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> and is also found in an inscription at Knockboy, Co. Waterford (<ref target="search.php?ciic=297">CIIC 297</ref>). In both instances the 
                        ending -GURN appears in place of an expected -GERN <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1991">(<bibl><author>McManus</author> <date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >7</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> </p></item>
                                    </list>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">In souterrain with 5 other Ogam stones in <placeName
                                type="townland">Ballyhank</placeName>, barony of <placeName
                                type="barony">East Muskerry</placeName>. (GPS coordinates
                                <geo>-8.609923,51.831600</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation">Unknown</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Last Recorded</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="lastLocation"><orgName>National Museum of Ireland</orgName> (<idno>NMI Ref. W.2, 2195?</idno>), 
                                <placeName type="county">Dublin</placeName>. The present location of
                            this stone may be accessed via the <ref
                                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=DU018-371----"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                                www.archaeology.ie</ref>. (GPS coordinates
                                <geo>-6.254558,53.340408</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="record">
                <head>History of Recording</head>
                <p>Discovered by <placeName type="county">Cork</placeName> antiquaries <persName
                        type="surname">Windele</persName>, <persName type="surname">Abell</persName>
                    and <persName type="surname">Hawkes</persName> in <date when="1846">1846</date>.
                        <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                                (<date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >92-3</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> records the removal of all ogham
                    stones from their original location in the Ballyhank souterrain, <q>one of these
                        was purchased from the local farmer by F. M. Jennings in 1846, and presented
                        by him to the Royal Irish Academy (PRIA 3: 213, without any statement of
                        provenance): in 1849 Windele removed the remaining stones to his own
                        residence</q>. All six were later re-united in the National Museum of Ireland collection.
                </p>
            </div>
